Hey Pablo, thanks for putting this together. After our conversations, I did a big refactor of the sidequest feature. Let me give some context, so @rin-st can also review.

You version was _simple_ in a sense that it was in a single file, but it was hiding a lot of complexity and had a lot of coupling.

I decided to do an architectural refactor (without getting too crazy). My main goal was to make it clear, simple, and maintainable (if we add / remove sidequests). Main pieces:

- `sideQuests/schema.ts`: The source of truth for the sidequest config (since we are not using the database to save the config, as in challenges). `SIDEQUESTS` will contain all the data that we need (e.g. link to a guide).
- `sideQuests/checks.ts`: It holds the check function for each side quest.
- `sideQuests/index.ts`: Export the main function to be used `fetchSideQuestsSnapshot`. Takes a `user` as a parameter. Changes from your approach:
  - Only saves completed sidequest to the database. I think `pending` state was a bit confusing, and we were adding a lot of unnecessary data. I think this is enough for the UI too.
  - Skip completed side quest (not sure if you had this)
  - Removed the `sidequest` object "prefix" in the new database field (`sidequests: {data}` => `{data}`)
- `sideQuests/types.ts`: just needed types.

- `onchainData/zerion.ts`: wraps Zerion API calls. (Also added some throws and console.errors)

----

